    <prp:abstract>Here we propose for 3.3 hrs with ALMA in Band 6 and a resolution of 0.03 arcesec to image V410 X-ray 2 in Taurus.  This object has previously been classified as a transitional disk (i.e., a disk with an inner hole). However, it is subject to a high extinction, Av~22, which may indicate it is actually an edge-on disk. Distinguishing between the two scenarios is important, since in the former case V410~X-ray 2 would be the faintest transitional disk in Taurus to date, implying we will find many more cavities amongst the low-millimeter-luminosity disks.  Also, it would be one of the best known candidates where the inner hole is due to photoevaporation.   If V410 X-ray 2 is actually an edge-on disk, it would serve as a cautionary tale against identifying an object as a transitional disk if it has a high extinction.  This would be a relatively simple, clear test for ALMA to undertake.</prp:abstract>
